# TIA: Target Independent Assembly

```tia
// configuration points of the translation unit
#file = "...";
#version = "0.1.0";

// configuration point of the definition
[!0]
// a global data definition
def x : i32 = 42;

// configuration point of the declaration
[!1]
// a global data declaration
def y : i64;

// configuration can be inline or out-of-line
[
  linkage = public,
]
// a global function declaration
def f : (i32, i32) -> i32;

// configuration point of a type definition
[ ... ]
// a global type definition
type t = struct { 
  r : f64,
  i : f64,
}

[
  linkage = public,
  debug = g_dbg,
]
// a global type definition
def g : (a : i32, b : i32) -> i32 {
  add : i32 %0, a, a
  add : i32 %1, b, b
  mul : i32 %2, %0, %1
  ret : i32 %2
}

!0 = {
  ...
}

!1 = {
  file = "...",
  line = 10,
  column = 1,
}

!dbg = {
  file = "...",
  line = 15,
  column = 1,
}

```

## Semantics

global configuration applies to a single translation unit.
there is no way of importing another translation units symbols
into the current translation unit, rather it is a prerequisite
that external symbols are declared in the current translation unit.
Then the linker combines these symbols when stitching together
different object files.

to support that workflow, it is possible to declare a symbol as
many times as one wants in a single translation unit, as long as
each declaration is compatible.

the visibility of a symbol between translation units is controlled by
the 'linkage' configuration. We are following the ELF standard here
for what is meant by each option of linkage.

additionally, there will be DWARF debugging information embedded into
the configuration points, allowing for DWARF debugging information to
be emitted into the object file.

The goal is to define an abstract assembly language, which fits in the
layer between a high-level programming language, such as C, and the
target assembly language such as x86-64.
This emitted assembly has to live in an ecosystem, and the other major
parts of that ecosystem are the ELF object file format, the DWARF debugging
information, and the x86-64 SystemV ABI.

```ebnf

module = { tag | [ meta ] def } ;
tag    = "#" id "=" expr ";" ;
meta   = "[" { mexpr [","] } "]" ;
mexpr  = id "=" literal ;

def = typedef
    | dbgdef
    | "def" id ":" type "=" expr ";" ;

typedef = "type" id "=" type ";" ;
dbgdef  = "dbg"  id "=" "{" { mexpr [","] } "}" ";" ;

type = struct-type
     | union-type
     | array-type
     | fn-type
     | "void"
     | "ptr"
     | "i8"
     | "i16"
     | "i32"
     | "i64"
     | "u8"
     | "u16"
     | "u32"
     | "u64"
     | "f32"
     | "f64"
     | id ;

struct-type = "struct" "{" { elem [","] } "}" ;
union-type  = "union"  "{" { elem [","] } "}" ;
enum-type   = "enum"   "{" { enum-elem [","] } "}" ;
array-type  = "[" type integral "]" ;
elem        = "id" ":" type ;
enum-elem   = "id" ["=" expr] ;

literal = string
        | char
        | integral
        | float ;

expr = primary
     | unop primary
     | primary { binop primary } ;

```

## Module

A module is a translation unit, it defines a set of names which have linkage, type, and value.

for the first version we are targeting the ELF format. And our notions of linkage type and value will 
lower to ELF notions of linkage type and value.  

a name may have metadata associated with it, the purpose of which is primarily debugging information in the form of 
DWARF, however the syntax of metadata is deliberately free-form to allow for extension as necessary within the compiler.

### Linkage

a symbol may be 

- internal (private)
  an internal symbol is not visible outside of the module which contains it's definition.
  and it is unreachable from other modules. an interal symbol may have a name which is shared 
  with a symbol in another module, and these symbols will not conflict with one another.
- external (public)
  an external symbol is visible to all other modules, and is reachable from all other modules.
  The definition of a public symbol must be unique between all modules which are intended to be 
  linked together.
- overridable (public)
  an overridable symbol is visible to all other module, and is reachable from all other modules.
  the definition of an overridable symbol may be shared with a definition of an external symbol 
  in another module, and in this case the external symbol shall take precendence over the overridable
  symbol. an overridable symbol may not be overriden by another overridable symbol.


§ ELF32 - Book 1 - Symbol Table

a symbol may be

- STB_LOCAL: Local symbols are not visible outside the object file containing their definition. 
  Local symbols with the same name may exist in multiple files without interfering with one another
- STB_GLOBAL: Global symbols are visible to all other object files being combined. One files definition
  of a global symbol will satisfy another file's undefined reference to the same global symbol
- STB_WEAK: Weak symbols resemble global symbols, but their definitions have lower precedence.
- STB_LOOS Environment Specific Usage
- STB_HIOS Environment Specific Usage
- STB_LOPROC Processor Specific Usage
- STB_HIPROC Processor Specific Usage
Note: STB_WEAK is useful when a standard library provides a symbol which is allowed to be overriden by 
  another equivalent symbol at load time. This is often used to override malloc/realloc/free with another 
  implementation when using C. such as replacing glibc malloc with jemalloc or similar.

the lowering proceeds as follows:

internal    -> STB_LOCAL
external    -> STB_GLOBAL
overridable -> STB_WEAK

### Symbol Type

a symbol may have type

i8, i16, i32, i64, u8, u16, u32, u64, f16, f32, f64,
array, struct, union, enum, ptr, (...) -> ...


§ ELF32 - Book 1 - Symbol Types

a symbol may have type:

- STT_NOTYPE: type unspecified
- STT_OBJECT: The symbol is associated with a data object, such as a variable, array, etc...
- STT_FUNC: the symbol is associated with a function or other executable code
- STT_SECTION: The symbol is associated with a section. Symbol table entries of this type
     exist primarily for relocation and normally have STB_LOCAL binding
- STT_FILE: the source file associated with the object file
- STT_LOOS Environment Specific Usage
- STT_HIOS Environment Specific Usage
- STT_LOPROC Processor Specific Usage
- STT_HIPROC Processor Specific Usage

the lowering proceeds as follows:

i8, i16, i32, i64, u8, u16, u32, u64, f16, f32, f64, array, struct, union, enum, ptr 
  -> STT_OBJECT

(...) -> ...
  -> STT_FUNC

NOTE: Research the Usage of STT_SECTION, STT_LOOS, STT_HIOS, STT_LOPROC, STT_HIPROC
and confirm that STT_FILE is used in debugging information, or if DWARF Repeats this 
information.

### Symbol Value

when a symbol has a type which is representable as a sequence of bytes, and it has a 
constant initializer within the text of the program, that constant initializer may be 
emitted into the object file.

When a symbol is represented by a sequence of instructions, those instruction shall be 
listed immediately following the definition of the symbol.

the lowering proceeds as follows:

i8, i16, i32, i64, u8, u16, u32, u64, f16, f32, f64, array, struct, union, enum, ptr

(...) -> ...
may appear immediately after the definition of the symbol.

