## Types

### Integers

the signed integer types (i8, i16, i32, i64) and unsigned integer types (u8, u16, u32, u64) are stored in two's 
compliment notation and they have defined behavior on all arithmetic operations. Different operations will have 
different defined behavior. the default arithmetic operations are presumed to model arithmetic as it is understood,
thus where the operations would cause an incorrect result a trap will occur.
There will also be wrapping arithmetic which will allow the signed and unsigned values to wrap around modulo the 
bit length.
There will also be saturating arithmetic which will pin the result to the maximum or minimum value when the value would 
wrap around.

-> traps and exceptional behavior

### Floats

The floating point types (f32, f64, f16?) are stored according to the IEEE 754 standard, and their behavior follows from 
that document.

### Structures

A structure type is a contiguous arrangement of types. layed out in the order that they are declared within the 
structure definition. There is padding between the elements, which is placed when the natural alignment of adjacent 
elements would create unaligned accesses to an element. For instance if a u8 element is immediately followed by a 
u64, there would be 7 bytes of padding between the two elements, to ensure that the u64 was stored on an 8 byte boundary.

-> forward declarations
-> addresses
-> element access

### Unions

A union type is a contiguous arrangement of types, layed out on top of eachother, such that they share the same bytes in 
memory. Thus only one element of a union type is valid at a time, and it is undefined behavior to access an uninitialized
element of a union. 

The common pattern is to pair an enumeration with a union within a structure, such that the currently active element is 
disambiguatable by checking the currently active tag. Whether or not the language will define syntax for this pattern is 
undecided. leaving it off allows for greater compatibility with the existing ecosystem, and having it means for an easier 
time of writing correct code by default. Where possible, access to the union is checked by the compiler, and errors will be 
emitted. 

### Enumerations

an enumeration is a sequence of names each defined implicitly as one greater than the previous, starting from zero.
the enumeration is backed by a signed 32 bit integer by default, this may be overriden.
each elements value may be overriden by an expression. This expression is only allowed to be a integer constant or
an expression which evaluates to an integer constant.
The enumeration elements themselves cannot exceed the capacity of the backing type, and an error is emitted should this
happen.

### Pointers

Pointers, or commonly Program Adresses are sequences of bits which refer to another location reachable within the programs 
allocated memory. A pointer could hold the address of a value on the stack, in the heap, or in the constant or variable 
data sections of the program binary. A pointer when it points to some memory is only valid to access as long as the memory 
being pointed to is alive. The 'backing' memory has some lifetime associated with it. This is common for stack local variables,
and the lifetime analysis is well-understood. The lifetime of constants and globals in program variable and constant sections are 
also well understood. The difficult points are pointers to the heap, and pointers stored within the heap.

a pointer to the heap is only valid for as long as the dynamically allocated memory is valid, which begins at the point of allocation 
and ends at the point of deallocation. These points are arbitrary if not given any other rules however. And so access to a pointer 
into the heap is uncertain, it could be safe, or it could be undefined behavior.

the issue is this:

fn f(...) -> ptr {
     var a : ptr = malloc(...);
     ...
     return a;
}

fn g(a: ptr) -> void {
     ...
     free(a);
