between f and g, any number of functions could be called. and functions which cross library layers and module layers could be called. 
and given that a pointer is `just` an address, its value could have been stored somewhere else to be incorrectly used after g is called,
freeing it. This can occur in code the user has written and controls, or in code the user does not write and does not control. in either
case the view that pluto has on the pointer is restricted to just the view of the functions 'f' and 'g', should these be defined in the 
same module. 

This means something more is required. in rust, the rules of borrowing are used to track ownership and lifetime of allocated memory between 
function boundaries. in c++ RAII and smart pointers are used to keep track of allocated lifetime and ownership, in C this problem is left 
to the carful hands of the programmer. in interpreted languages garbage collection alogorithms are used which keep track of ownership and 
lifetimes separately from the programmers concern.

